body:
### Summary of the new feature / enhancement

Selecting just the first occurrence in a [`switch` statement](https://docs.microsoft.com/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.core/about/about_switch) is a quiet common usage (which also appears from the given examples).
It would be nice to have a `-First` (or something similar, as e.g. `-FirstMatchOnly`, `-AutoBreak`) switch to automatically break after the first match. 
This will prevent repeating myself with `; break` statements or possibly forget it.

In other words, current statement:

```PowerShell
switch (2, 4)
{
    1 {"It is one."; Break}
    2 {"It is two." ; Break }
    3 {"It is three." ; Break }
    4 {"It is four." ; Break }
    Default {"No match found."}
}
It is two.
```

Wishful thinking:

```PowerShell
switch (2, 4) -First
{
    1 {"It is one." }
    2 {"It is two." }
    3 {"It is three." }
    4 {"It is four." }
    Default {"No match found."}
}
It is two.
```

